[30;1m61 | [0m[35m    In the present implementation, a 'window' around spikes is first[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m    specified. For example, if a window of 100 ms is taken, we will[0m
[30;1m63 | [0m[35m    take the correlation at lags from -50 ms to +50 ms around the spike peak.[0m
[30;1m64 | [0m[35m    In theory, we can have as many lags as we have samples. Often, this[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m    visualisation is too high resolution and instead the lags are binned[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m    (e.g. -50 to -45 ms, ..., -5 to 0 ms, 0 to 5 ms, ...., 45 to 50 ms).[0m

[30;1m52 | [0m[35m    In the extracellular electrophysiology context, a correlogram[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m    is a visualisation of the results of a cross-correlation[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35m    between two spike trains. The cross-correlation slides one spike train[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35m    along another sample-by-sample, taking the correlation at each 'lag'. This results[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m    in a plot with 'lag' (i.e. time offset) on the x-axis and 'correlation'[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35m    (i.e. how similar to two spike trains are) on the y-axis. In this[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m    implementation, the y-axis result is the 'counts' of spike matches per[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m497[0m[34m of [0m[33m1147[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m

[30;1m542 | [0m[35m        pairs of spikes (skipping those when outside of the window).[0m

[30;1m58 | [0m[35m    implementation, the y-axis result is the 'counts' of spike matches per[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m    time bin (rather than a computer correlation or covariance).[0m
